<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Race To Harvest Oranges by Machine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) -- Little has changed over the past few  
hundred years in how oranges are picked. People climb up a ladder, 
handpick the fruit into bags and later dump them into bins. 
</P>
<P>
	All that may be about to change.  
</P>
<P>
	The race is on to develop a machine that can pick the fruit off  
of Florida's largest orange trees. Finding a mechanical harvester 
is a top priority for the Florida Department of Citrus. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers say the labor pool of human pickers is shrinking from  
the federal government's crackdown on illegal immigrants, costing 
the industry $54 million a season. 
</P>
<P>
	Citrus officials worry that, without enough pickers, growers  
will be forced to leave oranges on trees. They also believe that 
mechanical harvesting will lower costs for Florida growers and keep 
them competitive with Brazil, the world's largest orange producer. 
</P>
<P>
	The citrus department has earmarked $2.5 million in next year's  
budget for research and development. 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting a fruit harvester is priority No. 1,'' said Joseph  
Marshburn, a member of the Florida Citrus Commission, the governing 
board that sets policy in Florida's citrus industry. ``We want 
something that works, is fast and commercial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Farmworker advocates dispute growers' claims that there is a  
labor shortage and view efforts to develop a mechanical harvester 
as a way for growers to avoid paying competitive wages. 
</P>
<P>
	At least half of Florida's orange pickers are undocumented,  
illegal workers. Growers are unwilling to pay higher wages to 
career pickers, traditionally middle-aged black Americans, now that 
their source of cheap labor is drying up, said Greg Schell, an 
attorney for the Migrant Farmworkers Justice Project in Belle 
Glade. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have determined it would be cheaper to use a mechanical  
harvester,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mechanical harvesting is just in its infancy. But some citrus  
officials believe 75 percent of Florida's processed orange crop 
could be harvested by machine in 10 years. That is a considerable 
portion of the Florida orange crop considering almost all of the 
state's oranges are processed, or used for juice. 
</P>
<P>
	Oranges are the state's biggest crop, representing $1.1 billion  
of Florida's $6.2 billion in agricultural cash receipts. 
</P>
<P>
	A mechanical harvester would only be used on oranges headed for  
the juice processor. Oranges intended for table fruit would still 
be picked by hand to prevent bruising. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, mechanical harvesters would likely only be  
used in Florida. Most of the oranges produced in Arizona, 
California and Texas are sold as table fruit. Grapefruit would 
still be picked by hand since most of Florida's grapefruit crop is 
used as table fruit. 
</P>
<P>
	For years farmers have used mechanical harvesters for crops such  
as cherries, olives and apples. But oranges have proved tougher to 
pick by machine because their stems are thicker than other fruit, 
said Galen Brown, the state citrus department's harvesting program 
administrator. 
</P>
<P>
	Six types of mechanical harvesters are being developed under the  
aegis of the citrus department. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, only one type, known as the ``trunk, shake and catch''  
model, is available for commercial use. This past season those 
machines were used to harvest only 5,000 acres of Florida's 658,000 
acres of orange groves. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``trunk, shake and catch'' machines comes in two parts. On  
one side of a tree, a mechanical ``shaker'' on wheels grasps the 
trunk of the tree with two rubber donut-like hands and shakes the 
tree. On the other side is a long, mobile conveyor belt that 
catches the oranges and moves them into a bin. The bin is 
periodically dumped into a large truck. The shaker and catcher move 
along a grove row in tandem. The machines can only be used on trees 
with trunks 18 inches or larger. 
</P>
<P>
	Other mechanical harvesters being developed look like something  
from a sci-fi movie. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``canopy area shake and catch'' model, from afar, looks like  
toothbrush bristles attached to a crane. The ``continuous travel 
canopy shake and catch'' model has porcupine-like spikes that move 
through trees like a paint rollerbrush. 
</P>
<P>
	A few growers that have decided to try mechanical harvesting are  
taking a wait-and-see attitude and are leasing instead of buying 
the machines, which can cost anywhere from $100,000 to $300,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The various machines under development will reduce a grower's  
harvesting costs anywhere from 10 percent to 75 percent and are 
three to four times more productive than handpickers, Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Compton Enterprises, the Chico, Calif.-based manufacturer which  
developed one of the ``trunk, shake and catch'' models, estimates 
that harvesting costs using a standard crew of 20 to 30 men can 
reach up to $558 per acre. Mechanical harvesting, which requires 
only three operators, would cost $248 an acre, according to the 
company's estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers in other countries, most notably France, Italy,  
Israel and Spain, have tried developing mechanical citrus 
harvesters but with little success. Brazil, Florida's main 
competitor for orange production, is looking to the Sunshine State 
to see how mechanical harvesting fares, Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	If it does succeed, it could be the biggest change to orange  
picking in Florida since the Spanish began harvesting the fruit in 
the 16th century, said John Attaway, a retired University of 
Florida professor. 
</P>
<P>
	``This would be the first change. Period,'' said Attaway, who  
also is former director of scientific research at the citrus 
department. ``We've always picked it by hand.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
