<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Six Injured in Water Park Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AGAWAM, Mass. (AP) -- Two people remained hospitalized in  
critical condition Sunday following a weekend amusement park 
accident that left them trapped beneath a flipped raft. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of six people -- a family of four and their two friends --  
were hurt in the accident Saturday night on Riverside Park's 
Blizzard River ride. Hospital officials said injuries ranged from 
``bumps and bruises to near drowning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The most seriously hurt were John Pascone of Dayville, Conn.,  
and Susan Messier, 27, of Coventry, R.I. Both were listed in 
critical condition Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Park officials said the fiberglass-and-rubber raft carrying the  
two families overturned about 50 feet from the ride's end. 
</P>
<P>
	The six were apparently belted into the raft at the time, and  
may have been trapped face-down in about 2 1/2 feet of water. Other 
rafts were nearby when the accident happened, but it was not 
immediately clear if they struck the overturned raft or its 
occupants, park spokesman Ron Sevart said. 
</P>
<P>
	A ride operator witnessed the accident and help arrived within a  
minute, Sevart said. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, a woman was killed and 10 people were injured when a  
raft flipped on a ride at Six Flags Over Texas. Both Riverside and 
Six Flags are owned by the same Oklahoma City-based company, 
Premier Parks. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswoman Terrie Ward said the rides were constructed by  
different manufacturers and there have been no other similar 
accidents at other Premier-owned parks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
