<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Russians Found Alive in Bering Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE (AP) -- Six Russian boaters whose skiffs became  
separated from their companions while crossing the Bering Sea were 
found in good condition after being lost for four days, the Coast 
Guard said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The boaters had become separated from a larger group while  
making a 65-mile Bering Strait crossing from St. Lawrence Island 
off Alaska's west coast to Provideniya on Russia's Chukotka 
Peninsula. 
</P>
<P>
	A Coast Guard plane spotted four people in two skiffs on  
Saturday, about 30 miles east of Provideniya, said Coast Guard Lt. 
Cmdr. Brian Flory. 
</P>
<P>
	A short time later, two others in a third skiff were spotted by  
a Russian freighter. 
</P>
<P>
	All were hungry and thirsty, but did not appear to be seriously  
injured, Flory said. 
</P>
<P>
	The six were part of a group of 37 people, mainly Siberian  
Eskimos, who had set out Tuesday in 14 skiffs. They were making the 
six-hour crossing loaded with supplies and gifts from relatives and 
friends in Gambell. 
</P>
<P>
	Many residents of Russia's Chukotka Peninsula share the same  
Siberian Yupik Eskimo ancestry and language with residents of St. 
Lawrence Island. 
</P>
<P>
	The flotilla ran into rough seas during the crossing. Two people  
-- a father and son -- drowned when their skiff sank. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard had launched an intensive airborne search for  
three missing skiffs late Tuesday night. The search was called off 
Friday, but resumed Saturday after the Coast Guard received 
permission from Russian authorities to search on the Russian side 
of the maritime boundary. 
</P>
<P>
	A C-130 transport plane was able to drop a radio, food, gasoline  
and supplies to four people in two boats Saturday. They were taken 
aboard a Russian freighter bound for Provideniya and were joined by 
the other two people when they were found soon after. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
