<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bears, Colts See Room To Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Good thing this one didn't count.  
</P>
<P>
	While the Chicago Bears won their first exhibition game in  
almost two years Saturday night, the 9-6 victory over the 
Indianapolis Colts was more like an exercise in ugliness. For both 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than 500 yards in total offense. No touchdowns. Eighteen  
penalties totaling 134 yards. Anemic passing game. Running game, 
what running game? 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't real pretty,'' new Bears coach Dick Jauron said.  
</P>
<P>
	Granted, it was the first game of the preseason. But both of  
these teams were awful last year, and the regular season is just a 
few weeks away. 
</P>
<P>
	Peyton Manning looked more like the quarterback who struggled at  
the start of last season than the one who finished with all kinds 
of NFL rookie records. He went three-and-out on three of his five 
series, and finished 6-of-11 for 47 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was intercepted on his third series when Tom Carter,  
playing in his first game since breaking his collarbone last 
September, read his long pass to E.G. Green perfectly, stepping in 
front of the receiver and snatching the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like any first game of the year. We couldn't put two  
plays in a row together,'' Manning said. ``You'd like to go down 
the field bam-bam-bam. But we made some mistakes. It's a sign of 
growing. They missed some passes, but I missed some throws, as 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the Colts' offense didn't fare much better. Though  
backup Kelly Holcomb led Indianapolis' two drives that resulted in 
field goals, he was just 5-of-15 for 60 yards. Marvin Harrison had 
three catches for 34 yards, but Green caught two balls for nine 
yards and Jerome Pathon had 17 yards on two catches. 
</P>
<P>
	And the running game? Without No. 4 pick Edgerrin James, who's  
still a holdout, the Colts' leading rusher was Holcomb, who picked 
up 27 yards on three scrambles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was pretty much a typical preseason game. Too many  
mistakes, but we'll correct them,'' coach Jim Mora said. ``I 
thought we protected the quarterback pretty well, especially early 
in the game. We didn't run the ball very well. We didn't make many 
big plays on offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts' defense was solid, putting a lot of pressure on  
Chicago's quarterbacks. Indianapolis had three sacks, including a 
double-team on Cade McNown by Jason Chorak and Brad Scioli that 
cost the Bears nine yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think some guy welcomed me to the NFL,'' McNown, who's been  
in camp four days, said of the trash talk he heard. ``But I 
reminded him it was the preseason, so he wasn't allowed to welcome 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNown was only supposed to play one or two series at the start  
of the second half, but those were so forgettable -- three-and-out 
in a hurry on both -- Jauron gave him another chance. It ended up 
being one of the highlights of the game as McNown led an 
eight-play, 56-yard drive that resulted in Todd Sauerbrun's 
game-tying field goal. 
</P>
<P>
	While McNown didn't get the Bears to the end zone, he had a nice  
21-yard pass and two seemingly effortless bullets that resulted in 
pass interference calls against the Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	``He makes things happen,'' Jauron said. ``He did it in college  
and that's what we expected of him and that's what he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sauerbrun, who filled in at placekicker for the injured Jeff  
Jaeger, kicked two other field goals, including the 31-yard 
game-winner with 6:50 left. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to get back into it and get back into a groove  
again,'' said Sauerbrun, who tore ligaments in his knee in the 
third game last year and missed the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears' pass rush showed it still needs some work, but their  
biggest problem was penalties. It started with two flags on the 
first play of the game. Then, after Carter's interception gave 
Chicago the ball at its own 41, consecutive false starts by Greg 
Huntington and Marcus Robinson killed the drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Huntington also had two false starts on McNown's third series.  
</P>
<P>
	``I said earlier it wasn't pretty,'' McNown said. ``But at least  
we won.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
