<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 11:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paltrow Stars in 'As You Like It' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- Wearing a glam red strapless gown, a  
young woman scampers up and out of a trapdoor conspicuously placed 
center stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Quite a first entrance but then this is not any ordinary vision  
in scarlet. It's Gwyneth Paltrow -- Academy Award-winning actress, 
Talk magazine cover girl and once close companion of Brad Pitt -- 
now facing audiences as Rosalind in ``As You Like It'' at the 
Williamstown Theater Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Paltrow's appearance launched a ticket frenzy at the festival,  
at least for the two weeks she is appearing here in the Shakespeare 
comedy. One has to admire her pluck in confronting a Mount Everest 
of expectations and sold-out performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Not to worry, though. Paltrow acquits herself well, starting  
with her savvy choice of roles. Rosalind is one of the Bard's most 
endearing heroines, wise, witty and charming but not above being 
blissfully baffled by love. For the most part, Paltrow measures up 
to those adjectives. 
</P>
<P>
	Visually stunning, she looks as if she just stepped out of an  
oil painting by John Singer Sargent. Blond hair upswept, she 
resembles a young Grace Kelly, elegant but with just a smidgen of 
insecurity and sass thrown in to keep admirers off-balance. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosalind is that kind of woman. The character is basically  
proactive rather than reactive, which is why she is so appealing to 
today's theatergoers. Rosalind takes matters in her own hands, 
particularly the wooing and winning of Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	When Rosalind disguises herself as a man, you go along with the  
plan because of her determination, although even in pants, Paltrow 
manages to look radiant. So you know Orlando doesn't stand much of 
a chance, as Alessandro Nivola's moonstruck performance amply 
demonstrates. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet dewy sentimentality is never allowed to hijack the  
proceedings, even when all the characters find themselves in the 
Forest of Arden. It's depicted impressionistically rather than as a 
realistic leafy green refuge. 
</P>
<P>
	In director Barry Edelstein's eclectic, mostly modern-dress  
revival, a few tree trunks and twigs will suffice. The 
unsentimental mood is underlined by a jazz combo, placed upstage. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the men are garbed as if they were Day-Glo gangsters,  
wearing bright colors and black shades. Composer Mark Bennett's 
edgy background score complements the costumes. 
</P>
<P>
	Paltrow may be the draw but she is not the only attraction in  
this revival. Others command attention, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Cumpsty, as the terminally melancholy Jaques, has the  
hardest task -- trying to find a new way to proclaim ``All the 
world's a stage,'' Shakespeare's famous Seven Ages of Man speech. 
Cumpsty plays it clear and straightforward, which makes it all the 
more affecting. 
</P>
<P>
	In many Shakespeare productions, the comic characters are  
impossible to make funny for modern audiences. Not so here. A 
marvelous Mark Linn-Baker captures the verbal dexterity of 
Touchstone, the not-so-foolish fool, as well as his comic 
pratfalls. 
</P>
<P>
	Linn-Baker is matched in his physicality by Lea DeLaria, who  
portrays the rambunctious rustic Audrey as if she were a linebacker 
for the Oakland Raiders. Broad, bawdy and very funny, DeLaria looks 
like a demented Betty Rubble, a refugee from some Elizabethan 
``Flintstones'' who, when she is happily in love, scats along with 
the band. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the heart of the play is the courtship between Rosalind and  
Orlando. They don't battle as ferociously as the cantankerous 
lovers in ``The Taming of the Shrew'' or banter as effectively as 
the lovestruck duo in ``Much Ado About Nothing,'' but their 
sparring is just as effective. 
</P>
<P>
	The most satisfying moments occur in a mismatched minuet --  
beautifully staged by Edelstein -- involving Rosalind, Orlando, the 
poor shepherd Silvius and his beloved but uninterested Phoebe. 
Paltrow and Nivola are joined by John Ellison Conlee and Angelina 
Phillips in this delightful round robin that captures the delicious 
desperation of love. 
</P>
<P>
	The production draws to an end with a joyous rendition of the  
old Louis Armstrong anthem, ``It's a Wonderful World,'' sung by 
Larry Marshall, who plays Orlando's loyal servant Adam. 
</P>
<P>
	After Marshall finishes the song, Paltrow touchingly delivers  
the play's generous epilogue and then the two of them join with 
Nivola in a sweet, heaven-sent musical sigh that brings the curtain 
down. You can hear the audience sighing right along with them. 
</P>
<P>
	``As You Like It'' runs through Aug. 15.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 09:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Quality Studied in National Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GATLINBURG, Tenn. (AP) -- ``How's the air quality today?''  
</P>
<P>
	The question beckons from a new kiosk at the Sugarlands Visitors  
Center in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park, the main 
entrance to the most visited national park in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Monitors provide the instant answer with a real-time view of the  
Smokies' tallest peaks from a vantage atop the 2,600-foot Look Rock 
monitoring station, along with the current ozone concentration and 
other weather information. 
</P>
<P>
	Comparison scenes show the same vista on good days, when  
visibility stretches to nearly 100 miles, and the smog-filled bad 
ones, when there is no view at all. 
</P>
<P>
	The latter view is becoming increasingly common.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not getting any better from the standpoint of  
visibility,'' Smokies Superintendent Karen Wade said. ``And I think 
the trends are not very encouraging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Clean Air Act has produced significant reductions in  
air pollution in many parts of the country, there are indications 
conditions are getting worse for the Smokies, a half-million acre 
park on the Tennessee-North Carolina border, and the rest of the 
southern Appalachians. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists say naturally light winds predispose the region to  
some of the most frequent and lengthy periods of air stagnation in 
North America. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are in a hot spot,'' said Jim Renfro, air quality  
specialist for the park. ``We are downwind from a lot of 
(pollution) sources and a lot of (regional) growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One recent study found that, while sulfur dioxide emissions  
primarily from burning fossil fuels have declined nationally, the 
Smokies suffered a 21 percent increase between 1985 and 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Coal-fired power plants as far away as the Mississippi River and  
Ohio Valley blow into the Smokies and linger, causing haze and acid 
rain. 
</P>
<P>
	So do pollutants from trucks and cars, including those of the  
some 10 million visitors to the park annually, leading to the 
formation of colorless ozone that can make breathing difficult, 
particularly up on mountain trails. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, the Smokies for the first time began issuing public  
health warnings when eight-hour ozone concentrations exceeded 
federal and state health standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Unhealthy ozone levels were marked a record 44 times last year,  
twice as many as the year before. The park recorded its highest 
eight-hour concentration last Aug. 25 -- 123 parts per billion, 50 
percent above healthy standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Ozone levels have been slightly worse this summer. As of Aug. 5,  
there have been 18 days when ozone has exceeded health standards; 
by this time last year, there had been two fewer. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet on a recent sunny morning, the Sugarlands Visitors Center  
bustled with hikers and sightseers who barely noticed the 
air-quality kiosk as they rushed around for souvenirs and 
directions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is there a problem? I didn't know,'' said Delbert Hacker, 65,  
of Vincennes, Ind., as he paused to look at the graphics and the 
Look Rock monitor on the kiosk. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranger Pam Rodgers, who staffs an information desk near the  
kiosk, said people want to talk about it after coming down from 
Clingmans Dome, the Smokies' tallest summit. 
</P>
<P>
	First they ask what's happened to the fir trees, which are being  
destroyed by a nonnative insect. Then they ask what happened to the 
view, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The park and environmental groups have undertaken a  
subtle-though-ubiquitous campaign to tell visitors that air quality 
in the mountains sometimes is no better than in the cities they 
left behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been doing monitoring since the mid-'80s,'' Smokies  
spokesman Bob Miller said. ``But it took us a while to feel 
comfortable enough with our science so that we could say for sure 
that there was damage occurring to park species because of air 
quality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experiments in the Smokies have established that at least 30  
species of plants in the park are dying or have been damaged 
because of ozone and acid rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting the word out is taking several forms:  
</P>
<P>
	-- More air-quality kiosks will be installed at other Smokies'  
visitors centers. The information also is available on the Internet 
at www.nature.nps.gov/ard/parks/grsm/lookRockWeather. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The newsletter ``Smokies Guide. The Official Newspaper of  
Great Smokies Mountain National Park'' regularly contains articles 
on pollutants. In the latest issue a story headlined ``Air 
Pollution is Ruining Our Views'' said summertime vistas have been 
reduced by 80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The National Parks and Conservation Association has targeted  
the Smokies as one of the country's most endangered parks. Its 
volunteers are handing out postcards visitors can send congressmen 
urging tougher emission standards for old coal-fired power plants. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A new film for the visitors centers, produced by the Friends  
of the Great Smoky Mountains, talks for the first time about 
environmental concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	``The park may be a sanctuary but it isn't an island,'' the  
film's narrator says. ``Its natural treasures are threatened by 
sprawling human development and nonnative pests and diseases. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``The Smokies were named for their natural blue mist. (But)  
today, air pollution from vehicles and smokestacks hundreds of 
miles away muddies the skies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Wade, a Sevier County native, state appeals court judge and  
president of the Friends group, acknowledged that some local 
business people may worry about scaring off tourists, but said the 
park's obligation is its preservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides, he said, ``If you lived in this area for the last 50  
years like I have you know that the air quality is not as good as 
it was and the visibility some days is terrible. There are days in 
the summer when you can hardly see the outline of the 
mountaintops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's an unprecedented stand by the park. But Wade said it is  
justified. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel like the park is a barometer of what is happening in a  
much wider region,'' she said. ``And we have a duty and a 
responsibility to articulate the issue not only about how it 
affects the park itself but how it is affecting our neighboring 
communities.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 22:10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisco Gives Accounting Co. $1B Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cisco Systems, a leading maker of computer  
networking equipment, has agreed to invest $1 billion in KPMG LLP 
to aid the accounting and consulting firm's expansion onto the 
Internet, a published report said. 
</P>
<P>
	San Jose-Calif.-based Cisco was expected to announce the  
agreement Monday, The New York Times reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of the deal, KPMG will use the money to hire  
4,000 engineers and service professionals to develop and deliver 
Internet-based data, voice and video services to its clients, the 
newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the next 18 months, KPMG will build six technology centers  
-- four in the United States and two abroad, the Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Cisco will own a stake of less than 20 percent in  
KPMG, the U.S. unit of privately-held KPMG International, No. 3 
among the big five accounting firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives from both companies said they believe there is a  
winner-takes-all prize for companies that win the race to 
incorporate the Internet into their business strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a realization that you can be out of business in  
three years,'' John Chambers, Cisco's chief executive told the 
Times. ``Whoever moves quickly first are those who will benefit 
over the next 10 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Butler, KPMG chairman and chief executive officer, said  
the New York-based firm has been courting potential technology 
partners in recent months. One result was a joint venture announced 
in June with Qwest Communications International to provide order 
processing. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 20:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pan Am Ends With Spirited Send-off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- The 13th Pan American Games slipped  
into history with a closing ceremony Sunday featuring splashes of 
culture from across the Americas and a send-off from this Canadian 
prairie city's most famous rock band. 
</P>
<P>
	If the tone of the opening was intended to be inspirational,  
Sunday's closing struck a note of the celebratory. 
</P>
<P>
	Dancers meant to symbolize geese kicked off the evening, racing  
onto the field and forming the word ``Viva'' while a 15-piece band 
played a salsa tune. 
</P>
<P>
	As highlights of the competition played on the large screen at  
the far end of the stadium, some 2,500 athletes and coaches swept 
into Winnipeg's stadium en masse, an unruly gaggle who danced and 
swayed and gyrated to the beat. The flagbearer from Guyana did a 
little dance, dipping and swaying his South American country's 
banner. Two athletes carried hand lettered signs, ``Thank You 
Winnipeg.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the greatest cheers were for the athletes from the  
Dominican Republic, site of the next Games, who carried a huge sign 
lettered in English and Spanish, ``See you all in Santo Domingo 
2003.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even the more solemn moments of the event had their comical  
aspects. Just as in the opening ceremony, athletes started a wave 
during the speech of Mario Vazquez Rana, the head of the Pan 
American Sports Organization. Then, moments after he began 
speaking, a cloudburst drenched the field, prompting the athletes 
to scramble under the grandstand for cover. 
</P>
<P>
	The bittersweet extravaganza's headliners were The Guess Who, a  
1960s band from Winnipeg famous for such hits as ``American 
Woman,'' and ``These Eyes.'' The band opened with ``No Time,'' as 
athletes, volunteers and anyone who could get to the field huddled 
around the stage. 
</P>
<P>
	The band's appearance was a coup for games organizers, who  
wanted the city's most famous rock export to perform -- just as they 
reportedly did in 1967, the last time Winnipeg was the site of the 
Pan Ams. One member of the band says he can't recall a concert 
during the games 32 years ago, but officials said photographs of 
the performance, featuring matching houndstooth jackets, exist. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their experience will mean a lot -- a bridge over the  
generations from the last games to these,'' said Brian Koshul, a 
spokesman for the games. ``It's a time to say goodbye.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremony was a chance for Winnipeggers to express their  
mixture of sadness and relief that the folksy regional Olympics 
have come to an end. Those who seemed most melancholy were 
volunteers filing into Winnipeg Stadium for the closing ceremony. 
The city mustered 20,000 volunteers, outfitted them in 
salmon-colored shirts and khakis and dispatched them to 33 venues 
around the city. 
</P>
<P>
	For many, having a huge sporting event three years after losing  
its professional hockey team, the Winnipeg Jets, provided a needed 
boost. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since we lost the Jets, people have been a little down,'' said  
Tom Tierney, 52, a retired civil servant who volunteered for the 
boxing, volleyball and artistic gymnastics competitions. ``This 
brings us back up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the dignitaries joining the spectators were Jean Chretien,  
Canada's premier, and Johny Ventura, the mayor of Santo Domingo, 
Dominican Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	The lead act may have been from rock 'n' roll, but opera,  
calypso, merengue and cha cha rhythms added an eclectic feel to the 
event. A masked parade of Caribbean performers added swathes of 
purple, gold and red to the field at Winnipeg Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletes, led by the Canadians, jumped out of the stands and  
joined the dancers as the Dominicans raced around the edge of the 
field with their banner. After a lap, the Dominicans crowded around 
the stage for the dignitaries. Ventura jumped to his feet and 
danced with his compatriots. 
</P>
<P>
	The most solemn moment of the games came when the cauldron was  
extinguished and the flame symbolically passed to Santo Domingo. An 
aria was composed for the event, but the steady rain put out most 
of the fire anyway, taking away the drama. 
</P>
<P>
	Winnipeg now joins Mexico City as the second country to have  
been host of the Pan Ams on two occasions. The Canadian city's 
first event, in 1967, involved 2,400 athletes from 28 countries who 
took part in 23 sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the games were last held here in 1967, the community  
talked about that event for 30 years,'' said Larry Desrochers, the 
producer-director of the opening and closing ceremonies. ``I think 
Winnipeg and the country will talk about these games for the next 
30 years.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
