<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marathon Swim Results in Doubt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- The results of the Atlantic City  
Ocean Marathon Swim are in doubt after swimming's international 
governing body voted Sunday to uphold the suspensions of the winner 
and third-place finisher. 
</P>
<P>
	The doping panel of FINA voted to uphold the suspensions of  
David Meca-Medina and Igor Majcen of Slovenia, race director Sid 
Cassidy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The international swimming federation temporarily suspended  
Meca-Medina and Majcen in May, saying both tested positive for the 
steroid nandrolone during the Jan. 31 World Cup event in Salvador 
de Bahia, Brazil. FINA issued a letter Aug. 2 temporarily staying 
the suspensions and allowing the swimmers to compete in Atlantic 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Race organizers issued a press release Sunday explaining FINA's  
decision to uphold the suspensions, but no reason for the 
international governing body's reversal of its temporary stay of 
the suspensions was given in the release. 
</P>
<P>
	Meca-Medina won Saturday's race, completing the 22-mile swim  
around Absecon Island in six hours, 56 minutes and 43 seconds and 
breaking the course record by six seconds. Majcen came in third, 
finishing in 7:07:26. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Ocean Marathon Swim is part of the FINA World Cup  
circuit, their wins will be classified as ``provisional'' and their 
prize money will be placed in escrow, Cassidy said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to FINA rules, the swimmers may appeal the doping  
panel's decision to the International Court of Arbitration for 
Sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Cassidy said that in the event that the ban is upheld through  
the final round of appeals, second-place finisher Andre Wilde of 
Germany will be declared the winner, and those finishing behind 
Majcen will move up accordingly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
