<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 14:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Cap on Calif. Campaign Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A fund-raising free-for-all has broken  
out in California, where about the only rule governing donations to 
politicians running for state office is that the contributor must 
be a U.S. citizen. 
</P>
<P>
	Proposition 208, approved three years ago, briefly imposed  
limits on personal and corporate donations. But a federal judge 
threw the law out, leaving California one of six states with no 
caps on contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Gray Davis disclosed last week that he raised nearly $6.4  
million in the first half of the year, more than three years before 
he faces re-election. Much of the money has come from firms, groups 
and people with a direct interest in legislation he is considering. 
</P>
<P>
	The total drawfs that of his predecessor, Pete Wilson, a  
Republican who collected one-fifth that amount in the six months 
after he first took office in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis is not alone. Big donations from casinos, insurance  
companies and others with an interest in legislation helped 
lawmakers collect at least $18.2 million so far -- in this 
non-election year. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of caps on political donations may have accelerated  
the frenzy, with some politicians intent on stocking war chests as 
insurance against new regulations already in the pipeline. 
</P>
<P>
	A campaign-finance bill that would limit donations is pending in  
the Legislature. Future court action could revive Proposition 208, 
and a similar ballot measure will go to voters next year if 
proponents gather enough signatures. 
</P>
<P>
	``The object is to get as much money in as possible so if either  
of these things occur, they'd at least have money in the bank. That 
is driving the find-raising activities,'' said Tony Miller, a 
former top state elections official and the co-author of the two 
initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``People assume what we're seeing is influence-buying, and that  
is very harmful to the democratic process,'' Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	The frenetic fund raising in a non-election year has touched off  
more than the usual grumbling from good-government advocates. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer watchdog Ralph Nader said he was so disgusted by Davis'  
fund-raising that he felt compelled to inject himself into 
California politics from his Washington, D.C., headquarters. He 
demanded that Davis freeze his efforts to collect new donations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times, in an editorial Thursday, lamented that  
contributors' ``seemingly endless access to the governor and 
legislators looks bad, no matter what the reality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis' chief political adviser, Garry South, denies that  
campaign contributions win access to the governor's ear, and said 
potential new donation restrictions haven't caused Davis to 
intensify fund-raising. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis is far more concerned about having to fight off wealthy  
challengers, South said. Davis came from behind to beat two 
self-financed candidates, Al Checchi and Rep. Jane Harman, in the 
1998 primary. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know who's out there,'' South said, adding that none  
of the current campaign-finance proposals would restrict rich 
candidates from spending unlimited sums on their own campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	But it is likely that other politicians are stepping up their  
fund-raising efforts due to the potential for donation 
restrictions, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	California, home to Hollywood, Silicon Valley, oil conglomerates  
and huge agricultural concerns, has a seemingly endless pool of 
millionaires and monied business interests eager to feed 
politicians' appetite for campaign money. 
</P>
<P>
	But Miller is bent on getting contribution limits passed by  
voters again and on protecting the new rules from court challenges. 
He thinks he has crafted just such an initiative this time around, 
and believes he will have enough signatures in coming days to place 
it on the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	History is on his side.  
</P>
<P>
	Every campaign-finance initiative on the California ballot in  
recent years has passed except one, he notes. The one that failed, 
Proposition 212 in 1996, was competing against a similar measure -- 
Proposition 208 -- and fell just short of 50 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
