<DOCNO> APW19990808.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 19:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Touts Texas' Education Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush urged the National Urban  
League Conference Sunday to consider Texas a model for changes that 
can be made on a national level. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential front-runner touted Texas' success  
at improving public education, noting that student test scores in 
the state's public schools have risen across the board, 
``especially (for) African American and Hispanic students.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Bush told the 4,000 black community and business leaders and  
activists about the abolition of social promotion of Texas students 
as a step toward ensuring that all students are able to ``access 
the American dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen what works in this state. We've raised the bar of  
expectations,'' Bush said. ``We've aligned authority and 
responsibility where it belongs, at the local level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's appearance at the Urban League's annual convention is  
part of his drive to appeal to ethnic minority voters, who have 
historically supported Democratic candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	The appearance came two weeks after Bush's absence from the  
annual convention of the National Council of La Raza, a Hispanic 
advocacy group, drew sharp criticism from his opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Bush turned down a chance to speak at a meeting of  
minority journalists in Seattle, though he was campaigning in that 
city at the time. He eventually made a brief appearance at that 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-day Urban League conference is drawing top candidates  
from the 2000 presidential race. Bush was the first of several 
contestants slated to appear. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, the front-runner for next year's  
Democratic nomination, is due to address the convention Monday. His 
closest Democratic rival, former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, is 
to speak Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, advocating what he called ``the hard work of compassion,''  
told the group that government money should support groups with 
successful social-aid programs -- such as faith-based organizations, 
churches, synagogues and charities. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've had success because they change lives by changing  
hearts, but they don't have the resources they need to continue 
waging the war,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 12:12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  French Troops Clash With Albanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians angry  
over the division of their town hurled stones and taunted French 
peacekeepers again Sunday, demanding free movement across a bridge 
into the Serb district. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second day of clashes between protesters and French  
troops on the bridge in the northwestern mining town of Kosovska 
Mitrovica, underscoring the continuing difficulties peacekeepers 
face in imposing peace on a province torn by ethnic hatreds. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort designed to help NATO-led troops impose law and  
order in Kosovo, a group of around 500 new civilian police from 10 
nations, including the United States, reported for duty Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	They are the first group to finish training for a planned  
3,100-strong international police force. The European Union envoy 
to Kosovo, however, has questioned whether the force was enough to 
stem the nearly daily violence between Kosovo's ethnic Albanians 
and Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	At Kosovska Mitrovica, French troops have been trying for weeks  
to prevent frictions by barring most traffic across the bridge over 
the Ibar river, separating the two communities' neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Around 150 young ethnic Albanian men threw stones at troops  
blocking the bridge Sunday with an armored personnel carrier, 
waving red-and-black Albanian flags and cursing the soldiers as 
``terrorists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least one protester was arrested. One French soldier was led  
away dazed by his comrades after a stone struck him in the face. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to cool down the tension,'' said French Capt.  
Bertrand Bonneau. ``We try to understand they are impatient. We 
must remain vigilant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's incident was on a smaller scale than a confrontation  
the previous day when up to 1,000 ethnic Albanians tried to cross 
the bridge, where hundreds of Serbs were waiting, taunting them 
with profanity. The peacekeepers forced back the crowd, arresting 
four people. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Sunday, NATO officials said French troops opened fire when  
gunmen attacked a Serb residential district in Kosovska Mitrovica 
using small arms and grenades. One attacker was arrested, the 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although more than 35,000 NATO-led peacekeepers are now in  
Kosovo, murders, abductions and other violence are the daily norm. 
The victims now are most often Serbs targeted by ethnic Albanians 
seeking revenge for more than a year of savage Serb repression that 
ended in June, after Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed 
to pull his troops out of the Serbian province in exchange for an 
end to a NATO bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The peacekeepers have been unable to stem the violence, and  
their representatives argue that as a military force, their primary 
job is not to act as police. 
</P>
<P>
	But EU envoy Martti Ahtisaari, the president of Finland,  
insisted NATO should continue to have the main responsibility for 
keeping order. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm afraid the role of the international police force hasn't  
been properly thought out,'' Ahtisaari, a chief broker of the 
Kosovo peace plan, told Finnish radio last week. ``The idea that 
3,000 police could maintain order ... is out of this world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In apparent ethnic violence this weekend, a Serb bar in Pristina  
was hit by a grenade attack that wounded three Serbs. Another 
grenade attack early Sunday left one suspect wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	The state-run Tanjug news agency said four Serbs in the village  
of Gornja Brnjica, north of Pristina, were wounded Saturday by 
shots fired from a passing car. The private Beta news agency said 
several Serb houses in the southwestern city of Prizren were burned 
down Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 12:12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  French Troops Clash With Albanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians angry  
over the division of their town hurled stones and taunted French 
peacekeepers again Sunday, demanding free movement across a bridge 
into the Serb district. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second day of clashes between protesters and French  
troops on the bridge in the northwestern mining town of Kosovska 
Mitrovica, underscoring the continuing difficulties peacekeepers 
face in imposing peace on a province torn by ethnic hatreds. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort designed to help NATO-led troops impose law and  
order in Kosovo, a group of around 500 new civilian police from 10 
nations, including the United States, reported for duty Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	They are the first group to finish training for a planned  
3,100-strong international police force. The European Union envoy 
to Kosovo, however, has questioned whether the force was enough to 
stem the nearly daily violence between Kosovo's ethnic Albanians 
and Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	At Kosovska Mitrovica, French troops have been trying for weeks  
to prevent frictions by barring most traffic across the bridge over 
the Ibar river, separating the two communities' neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Around 150 young ethnic Albanian men threw stones at troops  
blocking the bridge Sunday with an armored personnel carrier, 
waving red-and-black Albanian flags and cursing the soldiers as 
``terrorists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least one protester was arrested. One French soldier was led  
away dazed by his comrades after a stone struck him in the face. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to cool down the tension,'' said French Capt.  
Bertrand Bonneau. ``We try to understand they are impatient. We 
must remain vigilant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's incident was on a smaller scale than a confrontation  
the previous day when up to 1,000 ethnic Albanians tried to cross 
the bridge, where hundreds of Serbs were waiting, taunting them 
with profanity. The peacekeepers forced back the crowd, arresting 
four people. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Sunday, NATO officials said French troops opened fire when  
gunmen attacked a Serb residential district in Kosovska Mitrovica 
using small arms and grenades. One attacker was arrested, the 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although more than 35,000 NATO-led peacekeepers are now in  
Kosovo, murders, abductions and other violence are the daily norm. 
The victims now are most often Serbs targeted by ethnic Albanians 
seeking revenge for more than a year of savage Serb repression that 
ended in June, after Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed 
to pull his troops out of the Serbian province in exchange for an 
end to a NATO bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The peacekeepers have been unable to stem the violence, and  
their representatives argue that as a military force, their primary 
job is not to act as police. 
</P>
<P>
	But EU envoy Martti Ahtisaari, the president of Finland,  
insisted NATO should continue to have the main responsibility for 
keeping order. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm afraid the role of the international police force hasn't  
been properly thought out,'' Ahtisaari, a chief broker of the 
Kosovo peace plan, told Finnish radio last week. ``The idea that 
3,000 police could maintain order ... is out of this world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In apparent ethnic violence this weekend, a Serb bar in Pristina  
was hit by a grenade attack that wounded three Serbs. Another 
grenade attack early Sunday left one suspect wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	The state-run Tanjug news agency said four Serbs in the village  
of Gornja Brnjica, north of Pristina, were wounded Saturday by 
shots fired from a passing car. The private Beta news agency said 
several Serb houses in the southwestern city of Prizren were burned 
down Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
