<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Athlete Plans To Seek Asylum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cuban basketball player Juan Leopoldo Vazquez, who defected  
during the Pan American Games with the aid of a Miami-based exile 
group, was in Toronto on Sunday, where he plans to seek political 
asylum. 
</P>
<P>
	Ninoska Perez of the Miami-based Cuban American National  
Foundation, said Vazquez will remain in the Canadian city with a 
former teammate and fellow defector while he resolves his 
immigration status. 
</P>
<P>
	Vazquez defected Saturday night while attending a women's  
basketball game between Cuba and Brazil in Winnipeg, Manitoba. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to take a few days to think things out and see what  
he wants to do,'' said Perez. ``We'll get him an immigration 
attorney in Toronto, and from there on he'll decide what he wants 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perez said Vazquez has an uncle who lives in Miami, but his  
parents live in Cuba. His father is a member of the Communist 
Party. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke with his mother by phone Saturday, but asked a neighbor  
to delay telling her he was defecting so he wouldn't have to hear 
her crying. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very sad,'' said Perez. ``He talked to her and he never  
told her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For now, Vazquez will stay with Augusto Duquesne, a former  
basketball player on the Cuban national team who defected ``two to 
three'' years ago, according to Perez. 
</P>
<P>
	Vazquez eluded the Cuban security guards shadowing players at  
the sporting event long enough to contact representatives from the 
exile group. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had made contact with him. ... There were a lot of security  
agents around us, so he passed us a note telling us he would do it 
that evening during the Cuban women's basketball game,'' said 
Perez. ``We kind of walked out the door. We already had a running 
van outside and left to our hotel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, five members of Cuba's national basketball team  
defected while in Puerto Rico for the Olympic qualifying 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that here I'll have the liberty that I've always  
wanted, and I'll be able to do what I have always wanted to do in 
regards to cultural development,'' Vazquez told WLTV-TV in Miami. 
``Without any harm coming to me, without having to obey anyone. To 
be free like I've always dreamed.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
