<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inmates Give Aid to Dying Convicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALEM, Ore. (AP) -- Harvey Caron went to prison for killing a  
man. Now, on the inside, he helps people die. 
</P>
<P>
	He is one of 19 inmates, all but three of them convicted  
killers, who volunteer to care for the dying in the new hospice at 
the Oregon State Penitentiary. 
</P>
<P>
	The work ``gives me a reason, because there's not much in  
here,'' Caron said. ``I can't change what I did. All I can do is 
live my life the best I can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Caron, 45 and serving a life sentence, helps care for Lou  
Miller, a convicted murderer whose cancer has spread to his brain. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, 68, doesn't have much use for his fellow inmates. But he  
likes the hospice volunteers. 
</P>
<P>
	``When a man has been here so long, all those feelings of  
compassion get burned out of him,'' he said. ``This hospice thing 
opens people up more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With tougher sentencing laws and the spread of HIV, more and  
more inmates are dying behind bars. According to a 1998 National 
Institute of Corrections report, more than 800 inmates around the 
country were terminally ill in 1998, facing a death sentence 
imposed by no judge or jury. Oregon alone expects 800 inmates to 
die behind bars in the next 45 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in deaths has led to something relatively new in  
the field of corrections: the prison hospice. 
</P>
<P>
	Since inmates at the Federal Bureau of Prisons medical facility  
in Springfield, Mo., created the first in 1987, the prison hospice 
has spread to California, Colorado, Illinois, Louisiana, Maryland, 
Missouri, New York, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, South Carolina 
and Texas. Twelve other states are considering them, and South 
Carolina and Louisiana are expanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Oregon State Penitentiary opened its hospice in April.  
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of these people don't have any family who want to see  
them,'' said William Cahall, the prison's health services manager. 
``They may have alienated their families, or their families are not 
alive. This is our way of making sure they don't die alone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dying without family or friends is one of an inmate's greatest  
fears, said Tanya Tillman, hospice case manager at Louisiana State 
Penitentiary in Angola. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hospice is a philosophy,'' Cahall said. ``It basically means  
you have accepted that you have a terminal illness. You are not 
going to be seeking curative treatment. Nearly all your treatment 
will be pain control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In June, Briseldo Escobedo, 23, became the first inmate to die  
in the Oregon prison hospice. His family tried to bring him home to 
Medford to die, but the parole board refused after the mother of 
the man he had killed objected. 
</P>
<P>
	In the prison hospice with cancer, his last days were spent with  
his family and inmate volunteers around him. Using a special pump, 
he was able to give himself as much morphine intravenously as he 
needed to control his pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Oregon's assisted suicide law, a dying inmate can ask a  
physician to prescribe a lethal dose of medication. The Department 
of Correction is not looking forward to the day it is confronted 
with such a request. How could anyone be sure such a request was 
motivated by physical pain rather than the emotional pain of 
imprisonment? 
</P>
<P>
	``If a person is choosing suicide because of incarceration, I  
don't believe you could make the statute apply,'' said health 
services administrator Catherine Knox. 
</P>
<P>
	Prison administrators are finding that hospices may have more  
impact on the living than on the dying. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Texas Department of Corrections Michael Unit in  
Palestine, Texas, violent episodes dropped sharply after inmates 
began caring for the dying, Dr. Jason Calhoun, the department's 
medical director, said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really understand why,'' Calhoun said, but somehow the  
hospice changed how inmates dealt with life behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleet Maull, a convicted cocaine dealer who helped establish a  
federal prison hospice program and who founded the National Prison 
Hospice Association, said hospice restores humanity by giving both 
guards and inmates permission to care. 
</P>
<P>
	``It brings everybody's self-esteem up,'' he said. ``They begin  
to feel, `We are a community that takes care of ourselves. We don't 
just let our guys die with nobody taking care of them.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Wilson, who has been in prison for 11 years for a burglary  
that turned into a double murder and has no hope of getting out, 
felt his life change as he cared for Escobedo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hated who I had become,'' Wilson said. When he read in The  
Wall Street, the prison newsletter, about the hospice starting up, 
he asked to help. 
</P>
<P>
	A nurse brought Wilson to Escobedo's bedside in the infirmary.  
The two shook hands, Wilson sat down on the floor next to 
Escobedo's bed, and they started to talk. Over the next 36 days, 
they became brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	Each day, after working as a legal aid in the prison law  
library, Wilson, 30, visited the infirmary, often staying until 
midnight or 2 a.m. Wilson bathed and fed Escobedo and listened as 
the man explored his feelings about death. 
</P>
<P>
	``You feel a lot more human when you are involved in this,''  
Wilson said. ``I realized that I do care, and I do have that 
capacity within myself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of the reason I am doing it is to try to make up for what  
I did to those people (he killed), to make up for the things I've 
done,'' Wilson said. ``Part of it is for myself.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 15:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
