<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Says No To Grain Testing Plan / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- A federal agency won't support a proposal  
aimed at reducing the costly effects farmers attribute to the 
margin of error in grain testing for a toxin produced by the crop 
disease known as scab. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal was considered the most important of 10  
recommendations several North Dakota organizations submitted to the 
U.S. Grain Inspection, Packers and Stockyards Administration, which 
oversees grain-testing standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a grave mistake on GIPSA's part,'' said John  
Mittleider, executive administrator of the North Dakota Barley 
Council. ``I would think that they would understand the seriousness 
of the situation out here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vomitoxin, also known as deoxynivalnol or DON, is a byproduct of  
scab, a fungus that has cost wheat and barley farmers in Minnesota 
and North Dakota hundreds of millions of dollars in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed change the agency rejected would have required it  
to encourage private companies that buy and test barley to stop 
recording vomitoxin levels to the nearest tenth of a part of 
vomitoxin per million parts barley. Instead, it would have rounded 
the toxin's levels in barley to the nearest whole number. 
</P>
<P>
	The change would have helped make up for the margin of error in  
the testing, Mittleider said. 
</P>
<P>
	GIPSA Administrator James Baker said he couldn't support the  
proposal because test results rounded to the nearest whole number 
would not meet all the demands of domestic and export contracts 
that require stringent limits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reporting any result with a standard error of deviation could  
cause unnecessary confusion to buyers and sellers,'' Baker said in 
a letter to the barley council. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers make more money on barley with zero or very low  
vomitoxin levels because they can sell it as a beer ingredient. 
Brewers impose strict limits on how much of the toxin can be 
present in the barley they'll use in beer because it can affect 
beverage quality. 
</P>
<P>
	A small amount of vomitoxin can mean the difference between  
getting the higher price, and the margin of error alone in current 
testing technology can prevent farmers from getting the better 
price, Mittleider said. 
</P>
<P>
	GIPSA officials said they understand the magnitude of the  
problem. They pledged to implement some of the recommendations to 
try to improve accuracy in testing. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency plans to consult with the Agriculture Department's  
Agricultural Research Service to determine if the precision of 
field tests can be improved. Baker said GIPSA officials have 
contacted manufacturers of approved testing equipment to see if 
accuracy can be improved. 
</P>
<P>
	The recommendations were put together by the barley council, the  
North Dakota Grain Growers Association and GIPSA's Grand Forks 
field office after a study they conducted last summer found that 
demands for accuracy in the tests may not be consistently achieved 
with current testing technology. 
</P>
<P>
	A March report by the General Accounting Office supported that  
finding, and additionally found that North Dakota barley farmers 
lost about $200 million to scab and vomitoxin between 1993 and 
1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 12:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Address Bidding High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Bidding for use of the Internet address  
Drugs.com jumped wildly every few minutes before an auction closed 
with an offer of $823,456. 
</P>
<P>
	The business that submitted the winning bid Friday wanted to  
remain anonymous. 
</P>
<P>
	Several large drug companies and well-heeled speculators had  
expressed an interest, according to Eric MacIver, a 21-year-old 
Internet entrepreneur in Mesa, Ariz., who held an option on the 
Drugs.com domain name. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bidder will emerge as someone of note,'' possibly at a  
news conference in a week or so, said Steve Newman, executive vice 
president of online broker GreatDomains. GreatDomains, based in Los 
Angeles, was joined by Dotbroker.com in conducting the auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Internet names currently on auction include Loans.com with  
a high bid as of Friday at $480,000. ``We're going to set an end 
date in two or three weeks,'' Newman said of the Loans.com name 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Other names attracting early interest at auction include  
Tobacco.com ($150,000 bid), Slim.com ($200,000), Houses.com 
($65,000) and VideoDating.com ($35,000). No dates for the end of 
those auctions have been set. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the name Wallstreet.com was sold for $1 million to a  
Venezuelan company, but a relative bargain currently up for auction 
is Wallstreet.org ($45,000 bid as of Friday). 
</P>
<P>
	Last year Compaq Computer Corp. paid $3.35 million for the name  
AltaVista.com for its AltaVista search engine. Since then, Compaq 
sold a controlling stake in the engine to the Internet investment 
company CMGI Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	MacIver said that in May he purchased on option to buy the  
Drugs.com name from Bonnie Neubeck, owner of a Minneapolis Internet 
marketing company, when he had been considering an online drug sale 
business. MacIver later decided against forming such a company, but 
he is expected to get the biggest share of the auction price for 
Drugs.com. Mrs. Neubeck will receive the option amount. Neither 
would disclose terms of their agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 16:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paltrow Stars in 'As You Like It' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                     *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- Wearing a glam red strapless gown, a  
young woman scampers up and out of a trapdoor conspicuously placed 
center stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Quite a first entrance but then this is not any ordinary vision  
in scarlet. It's Gwyneth Paltrow -- Academy Award-winning actress, 
Talk magazine cover girl and once close companion of Brad Pitt -- 
now facing audiences as Rosalind in ``As You Like It'' at the 
Williamstown Theater Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Paltrow's appearance launched a ticket frenzy at the festival,  
at least for the two weeks she is appearing here in the Shakespeare 
comedy. One has to admire her pluck in confronting a Mount Everest 
of expectations and sold-out performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Not to worry, though. Paltrow acquits herself well, starting  
with her savvy choice of roles. Rosalind is one of the Bard's most 
endearing heroines, wise, witty and charming but not above being 
blissfully baffled by love. For the most part, Paltrow measures up 
to those adjectives. 
</P>
<P>
	Visually stunning, she looks as if she just stepped out of an  
oil painting by John Singer Sargent. Blond hair upswept, she 
resembles a young Grace Kelly, elegant but with just a smidgen of 
insecurity and sass thrown in to keep admirers off-balance. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosalind is that kind of woman. The character is basically  
proactive rather than reactive, which is why she is so appealing to 
today's theatergoers. Rosalind takes matters in her own hands, 
particularly the wooing and winning of Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	When Rosalind disguises herself as a man, you go along with the  
plan because of her determination, although even in pants, Paltrow 
manages to look radiant. So you know Orlando doesn't stand much of 
a chance, as Alessandro Nivola's moonstruck performance amply 
demonstrates. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet dewy sentimentality is never allowed to hijack the  
proceedings, even when all the characters find themselves in the 
Forest of Arden. It's depicted impressionistically rather than as a 
realistic leafy green refuge. 
</P>
<P>
	In director Barry Edelstein's eclectic, mostly modern-dress  
revival, a few tree trunks and twigs will suffice. The 
unsentimental mood is underlined by a jazz combo, placed upstage. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the men are garbed as if they were Day-Glo gangsters,  
wearing bright colors and black shades. Composer Mark Bennett's 
edgy background score complements the costumes. 
</P>
<P>
	Paltrow may be the draw but she is not the only attraction in  
this revival. Others command attention, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Cumpsty, as the terminally melancholy Jaques, has the  
hardest task -- trying to find a new way to proclaim ``All the 
world's a stage,'' Shakespeare's famous Seven Ages of Man speech. 
Cumpsty plays it clear and straightforward, which makes it all the 
more affecting. 
</P>
<P>
	In many Shakespeare productions, the comic characters are  
impossible to make funny for modern audiences. Not so here. A 
marvelous Mark Linn-Baker captures the verbal dexterity of 
Touchstone, the not-so-foolish fool, as well as his comic 
pratfalls. 
</P>
<P>
	Linn-Baker is matched in his physicality by Lea DeLaria, who  
portrays the rambunctious rustic Audrey as if she were a linebacker 
for the Oakland Raiders. Broad, bawdy and very funny, DeLaria looks 
like a demented Betty Rubble, a refugee from some Elizabethan 
``Flintstones'' who, when she is happily in love, scats along with 
the band. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the heart of the play is the courtship between Rosalind and  
Orlando. They don't battle as ferociously as the cantankerous 
lovers in ``The Taming of the Shrew'' or banter as effectively as 
the lovestruck duo in ``Much Ado About Nothing,'' but their 
sparring is just as effective. 
</P>
<P>
	The most satisfying moments occur in a mismatched minuet --  
beautifully staged by Edelstein -- involving Rosalind, Orlando, the 
poor shepherd Silvius and his beloved but uninterested Phoebe. 
Paltrow and Nivola are joined by John Ellison Conlee and Angelina 
Phillips in this delightful round robin that captures the delicious 
desperation of love. 
</P>
<P>
	The production draws to an end with a joyous rendition of the  
old Louis Armstrong anthem, ``It's a Wonderful World,'' sung by 
Larry Marshall, who plays Orlando's loyal servant Adam. 
</P>
<P>
	After Marshall finishes the song, Paltrow touchingly delivers  
the play's generous epilogue and then the two of them join with 
Nivola in a sweet, heaven-sent musical sigh that brings the curtain 
down. You can hear the audience sighing right along with them. 
</P>
<P>
	Paltrow's connection to the festival has been more than  
professional. Her mother, actress Blythe Danner, has been a 
longtime member of its informal acting company and, as a child, 
Paltrow spent many summers in this Berkshire mountain community and 
has appeared in other productions in past seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``As You Like It'' runs through Aug. 15.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
