<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Mixed in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen early Monday,  
partly on heightened tension over a possible North Korean missile 
test. Japanese stocks opened mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.26 yen in early trading, up 0.98 yen from  
late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
114.73 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 82.38  
points, or 0.48 percent, to 17,166.62 in the first 30 minutes of 
trading. On Friday, the average closed down 273.95 points, or 1.58 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the greenback gained ground against the  
yen after North Korea said Sunday it would ignore U.S. appeals and 
warnings to scrap an expected missile launch. 
</P>
<P>
	It was one of the strongest statements yet from North Korea,  
which Western military analysts say is poised to test an advanced 
version of a ballistic missile that it fired over Japan last year. 
North Korea claimed it had launched a satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan said it might respond to a missile test by severing one of  
the impoverished Communist country's only sources of hard cash -- 
money sent from Koreans living in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar is often regarded as a safe haven in times of  
international unrest. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's strength also derived from further buying among  
investors adjusting positions after the currency saw firm support 
despite hints of inflationary fears in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``After the U.S. jobs data, inflationary fears were triggered,  
but the dollar showed extraordinary strength around 114.30 yen,'' 
said Hideaki Inoue, manager of the international treasury division 
at Mitsubishi Trust and Banking. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the U.S. Labor Department reported employers added a  
larger-than-expected 310,000 jobs to their payrolls in July and 
that average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures, 
rose 3.98 percent from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.75 yen, up from  
122.90 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei index opened slightly higher  
after losing 4.3 percent over the course of last week on fears of 
rising U.S. interest rates and of a strengthening yen. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar's rise back above 115 yen supported sentiment  
Monday, and share prices are seen as having already factored in 
expectations for an increase in U.S. interest rates, market players 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 79.79 points  
to close Friday at 10,714.03. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 0.25 points, or 0.02 percent, to 1,420.43. 
The TOPIX closed down 10.34 points, or 0.72 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond was unquoted in early trading. On Friday, its yield settled at 
1.8050 percent and its price stood at 99.95 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
