<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nuke Reactor Vessel Finishes Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) -- A decommissioned 1,000-ton nuclear  
reactor vessel finished its voyage up the Columbia River on Sunday, 
docking safely just miles from a burial site for radioactive waste. 
</P>
<P>
	It took about 36 hours for tugs to bring the vessel, emptied of  
its uranium fuel, up 270 miles of river from the dismantled Trojan 
Nuclear Plant west of Portland, Ore. That included a two-hour 
precautionary stop early Sunday at Pasco to wait for daylight on 
the last 10-mile stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	The voyage ended at 9 a.m.  
</P>
<P>
	``It went very well,'' said Steve Nichols, project manager for  
Portland General Electric, the utility decommissioning the largest 
commercial reactor ever taken off line in the United States. ``It's 
been very routine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The river voyage past Portland made it the first commercial  
reactor of that size and level of contamination to pass so near a 
major American city, according to the Nuclear Regulatory 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	No demonstrators were on hand when the barge docked at the  
nearby river port of Benton, part of a region of south-central 
Washington that has been closely tied to nuclear development since 
World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, a handful of people stood atop a bluff a couple  
hundreds yards away with video cameras. 
</P>
<P>
	From Benton, the reactor vessel was to be towed about 30 miles,  
partially on public highway, to its burial site at the federal 
Hanford Nuclear Reservation. It was mounted on a 16-axle trailer 
with 320 wheels to support its enormous weight. 
</P>
<P>
	PGE already had shipped Trojan's contaminated steam generators  
upriver to Hanford since 1995, and the Navy often ships reactors 
from submarines and cruisers up the Columbia for burial at the 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it no longer contains its uranium fuel, the Trojan  
reactor vessel contains 15 times as much radioactivity as those 
objects, according to state officials. 
</P>
<P>
	However, after being filled with concrete and encased in  
6-inch-thick steel, the reactor was considered safe for shipment. 
Workers handling it wear no more protection than a hard hat. 
</P>
<P>
	The Trojan plant operated for 16 years, generating enough  
electricity to supply all of Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	It was shut down in 1993, two decades earlier than planned,  
after a series of problems including a faulty safety system that 
drew federal fines, an accidental release of radioactive gases and 
cracked steam tubes. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 800 spent but highly radioactive uranium fuel rod  
assemblies removed from the reactor over the years remain in 
storage at the Trojan site. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 15:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Warns of Tax-Cut Aftermath </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- President Clinton, seeking allies in his battle  
against the Republican tax-cut plan, warned the nation's governors 
Sunday that the $792 billion package would trigger ``huge cuts'' in 
Medicare, farm programs and other spending critical to their 
voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening a new attack on the 10-year, tax-cut bill passed by  
Congress last week, the president said Washington faces ``a 
generational challenge'': how to divide projected surpluses among 
tax cuts, debt reduction and popular federal programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we ought to blow it,'' he said. ``And if I can  
stop it, I will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans countered that Clinton and fellow Democrats would  
say anything to avoid shrinking government. ``The president wants 
more money so he can spend more money,'' Republican Sen. Don 
Nickles of Oklahoma told the National Governors' Association, just 
ahead of the president at the lectern. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Nickles left the door open to compromise, amid fears  
that the stalemate could result in another government shutdown. 
``I'm not nearly as pessimistic as other are about the process of 
reaching an agreement,'' Clinton said. ``I am determined to do 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He avoided confrontational language on the tax issue, and  
softened a planned critique of state health insurance programs for 
children. He chose instead to appeal for help and support from the 
state leaders. Then the former Arkansas governor mingled for more 
than 30 minutes with state executives from both parties. 
</P>
<P>
	He posed for pictures with Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, a  
former wrestler. They chatted about life in the ring. 
</P>
<P>
	As Clinton and Nickles made their parties' tax pitches to the  
governors, operatives for the White House and the Republican 
leadership in Congress hit the television news shows in a bitterly 
partisan debate that could shape the 2000 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans argue that the surplus is large enough to protect  
Social Security, Medicare and return money to taxpayers. Clinton 
wants a $250 billion tax cut, keeping more in Washington to reduce 
the debt and shore up Social Security and Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big thing that we have to do is get people to understand  
that tax reduction relief is possible,'' House Majority Leader Dick 
Armey, of Texas, said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's budget director, Jack Lew, accused Republicans of  
resorting to a ``cynical charade'' and ``a fiscal hoax'' to sell 
their tax cuts. His office released an analysis that said GOP tax 
cuts would trigger across-the-board spending reductions under a 
1990 budget law. 
</P>
<P>
	It said Medicare would be reduced by $32 billion over five years  
and crop insurance would lose $19 billion. Spending for veterans, 
day care and state programs that cater the needy would be 
eliminated or cut, said the study. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said there would be ``huge cuts in all these things.''  
After a lengthy explanation of the budget process, Clinton said, 
``To me, this is not politics. This is arithmetic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't seem to change any minds. Democratic governors, such  
as Tom Vilsack of Iowa, said they were skeptical of the GOP plans. 
Republican governors formed a united front behind Republicans in 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this isn't a good time to cuts taxes, when is it a good  
time?'' Gov. James Gilmore of Virginia said. 
</P>
<P>
	While making their case on taxes, Nickles and Clinton tackled  
other political problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Nickles hoped his appearance would end an angry dispute between  
the GOP governors and Republican leaders in Congress over a 
proposal to seek welfare money from the states to pay for tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you -- at least from this senator and I believe on  
behalf of all Republican leaders -- that's not going to happen. The 
(welfare) money will stay intact,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican governors were angry at not being consulted.  
House Speaker Dennis Hastert declined several requests to address 
the governors, raising suspicions that the issue wasn't settled. 
Worried they still had no such commitment form House Republicans, 
the governors were putting together a harshly worded resolution 
urging Congress not to take back the welfare money. 
</P>
<P>
	Though his remarks were more tame than aides had predicted,  
Clinton upset many governors, particularly Republicans, by 
questioning their work to get low-income children enrolled in a 
federal health insurance program. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1.3 million children have been enrolled in the program.  
Clinton said states should shoot for 5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican governors complained that the Clinton administration  
has been slow to give them approval to develop health insurance 
programs. And they said only 2.5 million children are eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just grandstanding,'' grumbled Republican Gov. John  
Engler of Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	Other GOP governors said they suspected Clinton was making  
trouble for a colleague -- Gov. George Bush of Texas, the leading 
Republican candidate for president. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas has the second-largest percentage of uninsured children,  
according to Census Bureau figures from 1996 to 1998. The figures 
were widely distributed by the Democrats. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
