<DOCNO> APW19990808.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 09:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Facts About Oil Trade Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Highlights of the case alleging unfair trade practices involving  
oil imports: 

</P>
<P>
	PETITION: Filed by about a dozen small independent oil producers  
organized under an Okahoma-based coalition called Save Domestic Oil 
Inc. Petition is supported by many other independents, but opposed 
by the major international oil companies. 

</P>
<P>
	CHARGES: That government-oil companies in Venezuela, Mexico,  
Saudi Arabia and Iraq sold oil in the U.S. market at ``less than 
normal value'' and that the government's subsidized such sales, to 
the economic detriment of the U.S. industry. These countries 
account for 60 percent of U.S. oil imports. 

</P>
<P>
	THE LAW: The anti-dumping laws enacted in 1930 prohibit selling  
imported products at lower prices than they are sold in home 
countries or below average cost of production, and prohibit 
governments from subsidizing production or export of such products. 

</P>
<P>
	PROCEDURES: Jurisdiction is divided between the Commerce  
Department's International Trade Association, and an independent 
agency, the International Trade Commission (ITC). 
</P>
<P>
	The petition is filed with Commerce, which decides if the group  
has legal standing, whether the product is being sold in violation 
of the law, and whether an action should be initiated. 
</P>
<P>
	If the case is accepted, the independent ITC then must decides  
whether the U.S. industry, or the portion of the industry subject 
to the petition, has been harmed economically as a result. The 
Commerce agency then decides what tariffs or penalties should be 
imposed. 

</P>
<P>
	APPEALS: If Commerce decides initially to reject the case,  
petitioners may appeal to the Court of International Trade, a 
process that can take several years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 18:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jarrett Rolling Toward First Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Just call Dale Jarrett Mr. Consistency. If  
he keeps it up, pretty soon you can call him Champ. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett dominated the Brickyard 400 on Saturday at the  
Indianapolis Motor Speedway, leading 116 of 160 laps on the way to 
his fourth victory of the season. That also built his margin over 
runner-up Mark Martin in the Winston Cup standings to 274 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brickyard is only the latest example of the way Jarrett and  
his Robert Yates Racing team have performed during the 1999 season. 
The victory gave him 16 top-five finishes in 20 races this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, it's been Jarrett, the son of a two-time NASCAR  
champion, who has been doing the chasing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot more fun being where we're at,'' said Jarrett, who  
has yet to win a series title and has finished third, second and 
third in the points in the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're in second and third, you have to rely on someone  
else having a problem for you to gain points. There were many days 
in the last couple of years when we finished second, third, fourth 
or fifth, and the problem was that the guy in front of us, leading 
the points, was the guy finishing first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the past two years, that guy was Jeff Gordon. But Gordon, a  
three-time series champion overall, is sixth in the points this 
year and, like everyone else, watched helplessly as Jarrett ran 
away with Saturday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's very, very tough right now,'' Gordon said. ``It's  
like they were just biding their time, getting those top fives 
early in the season and, all of a sudden, everything is clicking 
for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, they're getting wins.''  
</P>
<P>
	All four of Jarrett's victories -- matching Gordon and Jeff  
Burton for the season-high -- have come in the last 10 events. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Labonte, who followed Jarrett across the finish line  
Saturday -- nearly half a straightaway behind the winner's No. 88 
Ford Taurus -- said, ``It's awfully tough to keep up with him every 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``He drives this track so well. I followed him lap after lap  
after lap and he doesn't vary an inch, it seems. Those guys are 
just clicking on all cylinders right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just doing the best we can to keep up with him right  
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Parrott, Jarrett's crew chief for the past three seasons,  
says there are good reasons why the Yates team is racing with 
confidence these days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've stepped up our program,'' the son of longtime  
crew chief and team manager Buddy Parrott said. ``The biggest thing 
is the team. This isn't about Dale or me or Robert. It's about all 
of us. 
</P>
<P>
	``And behind us there's about 60 or 70 guys back at the shop,  
and that's what working. There's no single thing that you can put 
your finger on. ... Right now, everything is going good. We've got 
a lot of racing luck, and you just got to keep doing things like 
we're doing and things like we did here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett, who is now a two-time Brickyard champion, said he and  
his team are going to make it tough for anybody to catch them in 
the final 14 races this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``They see the races start counting down and they realize that  
their time is running out a bit,'' he said. ``It's a lot more fun 
to be in control of your destiny. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that I have a good team, and they've done their job  
totally in every respect this year. That's been the key. We've just 
been there week in and week out.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
