<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Corps Probes Wetlands Less </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers has retreated  
from its policy of enforcing the laws that protect the nation's 
wetlands, The Boston Globe reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1992, the Corps has inspected 40 percent fewer wetlands  
areas for possible violations, according to the Globe. Over roughly 
the same period, the agency accepted more applications to develop 
swamps, marshes and streams, according to the Globe's review of 
records from the Corps' 37 field offices. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, for example, the Corps rejected 8.8 percent of  
development requests; in 1998, it dismissed 3.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Also since 1992, orders to restore illegally damaged wetlands  
have fallen from 283 to 109, and field inspections have dropped 
from 8,149 to 5,141 in the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Corps is withdrawing its presence in enforcement,'' said  
Magi Shapiro, a former Corps employee who said she left the agency 
rather than approve development projects she felt should not be 
allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	``A program without enforcement is an invitation to break the  
law without consequences,'' Shapiro said. Her advocacy group, 
Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility, provided the 
Globe with the Corps records. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Corps officials, however, insist the decline in  
inspections and enforcement actions is not cause for alarm. They 
say the trend is partly due to fewer projects by businesses and 
others that would damage wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe we've substantially increased environmental  
protection over the past 10 years,'' said John Studet, chief of the 
headquarters regulatory branch of the Corps. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials say cuts in the number of regulatory staff -- from  
1,150 to 1,050 in the last five years -- have made them become more 
efficient. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year, more than 100,000 acres of wetlands are filled in or  
destroyed by development in the United States, killing wildlife and 
destroying an important protection from floodwaters and trap for 
pollutants that might otherwise reach tap water. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1972, the Corps, along with the Environmental Protection  
Agency, has been responsible for protecting the wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Corps employees say that recent budget and staff cuts, however,  
and a message from the top, have made them more accommodating to 
developers. At one office, staff were urged in a memo to avoid 
time-consuming, costly enforcement actions. 
</P>
<P>
	But Corps officials say the Clinton Administration is committed  
to preserving the nation's wetlands and has a goal to create 
100,000 more acres of wetlands than are destroyed by 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say only modest resources have been given to the Corps  
and the EPA, and the Corps has begun to transfer its 
responsibilities elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	At the New England Corps a separate enforcement division has  
been eliminated and more cases have been transferred to the EPA's 
Boston office, where there is only one full-time inspector and one 
part-time staff member. 
</P>
<P>
	Studet said the workload shift to the EPA makes sense, however,  
because the EPA has broader enforcement powers and a larger legal 
team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
