<DOCNO> APW19990808.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 11:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Offers Tax-Cut Plan Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Republicans on Sunday promoted a  
plan they said would delay their $792 billion tax cut while sparing 
the GOP the sort of political hits it took during government 
shutdowns tied to the budget standoff in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders said they would support legislation that would keep  
the government in business, at current funding levels, for as much 
as a year, in an attempt to counter President Clinton's promised 
veto of the tax package. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the way to avoid a train wreck,'' Senate Majority  
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said on ABC's ``This Week,'' using the 
political euphemism for a shutdown when the new budget year begins 
Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no need for that sort of thing. And it's  
irresponsible, too,'' said Lott, R-Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	He suggested legislation, known as a continuing resolution, that  
would keep the governing running ``for two weeks or a month or for 
a year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House's third-ranking Republican, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas,  
has called the measure ``a little trick'' that would put Clinton at 
risk of being blamed for a shutdown if he vetoed it -- as 
Republicans were when the government closed twice in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters, DeLay said, might have to wait for a break on their tax  
bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``If (Clinton) vetoes it, then maybe we'll have to wait for a  
real president that wants to give the American family a tax 
relief,'' Delay said Saturday on CNN's ``Evans, Novak, Hunt &AMP; 
Shields.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton might reconsider his position on the tax cuts as  
Republicans sell it to voters during the current congressional 
summer break, GOP lawmakers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that public opinion is going to come out strong for  
this package as it's better understood and we believe the president 
will respond to that,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, 
said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton believes the GOP cuts, to be paid with a projected $1  
trillion surplus over the next decade, are too large and endanger 
the nation's economic future. 
</P>
<P>
	He was telling state leaders Sunday at the National Governors  
Association meeting that a report by the White House budget office 
found the GOP plan would trigger automatic spending cuts in current 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The timing of the looming fight is sensitive for both parties as  
the 2000 elections near, with control of the White House and the 
House at stake. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, DeLay has said, planned to spend next year's $14  
billion annual surplus all along, to force Clinton to pay for his 
spending programs from the Social Security surplus, which both 
parties have promised to protect. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay has made no secret he would relish such a scenario, saying  
post-veto budget negotiations would occur with Clinton ``on his 
knees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not all GOP leaders were as strident.  
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether he shared that vision of a politically weakened  
president during budget talks, Armey said, ``No, of course not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are all going to be sitting at the table together,'' he  
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Republicans will not be there, however.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, told CNN's ``Late Edition'' that  
he voted against the tax cut because the projected surplus intended 
is a ``rosy'' image and ``a mirage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other Republicans show signs of backing off their tough talk.  
</P>
<P>
	In the latest indication that Republican budget strategy is in  
trouble, Lott said he would like to see a cut in the $7.4 billion 
farm aid package the House has approved -- and for which he voted 
when it passed the Senate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
