<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wis. Brewery Closes After 141 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) -- The former G. Heileman brewery officially  
closed Sunday after 141 years in the beer business, leaving more 
than 500 workers out of work. 
</P>
<P>
	A handful of workers will finish cleaning up and shipping this  
week, but manufacturing and packaging at the brewery has ended, 
said Lacey Logan, a spokeswoman for Stroh Brewery Co. of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Stroh announced Feb. 8 it would quit the beer business. It sold  
its brands April 30 to Miller and Pabst. Local officials hunted for 
a buyer and eventually reached James Strupp and his partner, John 
Mazzuto, of Platinum Holdings, a New York-based investment company. 
</P>
<P>
	The investors on Friday reached an agreement to buy the plant  
from Stroh for $10.5 million and run it as a contract beer-maker 
and bottler. But employment will drop to about 50 when the brewery 
reopens later this year, Strupp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strupp said employment could grow to 300 by 2003. The brewery  
will be known as the City Brewery, the name it carried at its 1858 
opening, Strupp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Local businesses that have done business with the brewery now  
must wait to see how they fit into the plant's future. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Heileman executive Randy Smith, hired by Platinum as a  
consultant and expected to serve as president and chief executive 
officer of the brewery when it reopens, said he has not yet lined 
up distributors. 
</P>
<P>
	``But clearly what I call the old Heileman network, to the  
extent it still exists, would be the place for us to look first,'' 
Smith said. ``They're familiar with us, with the people here. And 
they probably would be the most anxious to take on brands from The 
City Brewery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The G. Heileman Brewing Co. ran into financial problems in the  
1990s and declared bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	Stroh bought the plant in 1996. The last case of Old Style was  
packaged at the plant Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Platinum Holdings plans to produce beer for other companies and  
establish some new brands for distribution in the Upper Midwest. It 
may also produce bottled water, juice products and ethanol. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
