<DOCNO> APW19990808.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 09:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling on Oil Dispute Expected Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an unusual -- some say absurd -- trade  
dispute, a group of small oil companies contends four leading 
foreign oil suppliers are driving them out of business by selling 
the valuable commodity at artificially low prices in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	If the U.S. government agrees, it could impose a tax raising the  
barrel price of some imported oil by up to 170 percent. The four 
countries -- Saudi Arabia, Mexico, Iraq and Venezuela -- supply about 
60 percent of U.S. oil imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department was to decide Monday whether to let the  
Oklahoma oilmen's petition go ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Already the case has fractured the oil industry, pitting Big Oil  
against the struggling independent producers, and economists say it 
could put America's trade policy to a new test. 
</P>
<P>
	The oilmen's request for an investigation shocked trade experts  
who say oil prices are highly volatile and dictated by world 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's absurd about this case is Americans have been opposed  
to higher oil prices for my entire adult lifetime and here we have 
a case where the effect could well be to raise prices,'' says 
Robert Litan, a Brookings Institution economist. 
</P>
<P>
	``This involves a commodity that no one ever would have thought  
would be subject to an anti-dumping case,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	He is one of the most vocal critics of the federal law on  
illegal dumping -- when an imported commodity is being sold at less 
than normal value or below what it costs to produce it. 
</P>
<P>
	But Harold Hamm, who helped found a group called ``Save Domestic  
Oil'' to bring the complaint, argues the anti-dumping law is 
supposed to protect U.S. companies in just this kind of case. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oil is not any different. Dumping did occur and it put 100,000  
people out of jobs,'' Hamm, president of an Enid, Okla.-based 
independent oil company, said in a telephone interview. ``There's 
not anything absurd about it. Our only line of defense is the trade 
laws and I think we've got a very good case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The independent companies also believe the four countries  
unfairly are subsidizing oil production. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations, if found true, would amount to illegal dumping  
of oil in the United States and require Washington to impose 
tariffs and penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	A Commerce Department division, the International Trade  
Association, was expected to decide Monday whether the oilmen have 
the right to continue with their case. If they are denied, the 
independent producers can appeal to a special court, though the 
process could take years. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists and trade specialists say the case is weak, and  
some contend that if the oilmen are successful, it could result in 
a backlash against the anti-dumping law enacted almost 70 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of other users of the anti-dumping (provision)  
who do not want this case to go further. It puts a real spotlight 
on it,'' said Gary Hutbauer, a trade expert at the Institute for 
International Economics. 
</P>
<P>
	Already the case has had repercussions:  
</P>
<P>
	--The American Petroleum Institute, which represents the large,  
international oil companies, has pledged to fight it along every 
step, hiring a lawyer who specializes in bringing anti-dumping 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	--More than 100 organizations, companies and industry groups from  
airlines and truckers to farmers are opposed, arguing a favorable 
ruling would harm consumers by raising oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	--Mexico has delayed plans to phase out its tariff on U.S.  
natural gas imports until the anti-dumping case is resolved. 
Venezuela has denied the charge it is selling oil at below market 
value. 
</P>
<P>
	Some oil industry experts also are concerned about the fate of  
recent efforts to promote greater U.S. industry involvement in 
Saudi oil development. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the long term, its difficult to see who would benefit from  
this action,'' says Red Cavaney, president of the American 
Petroleum Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists say the nature of world oil markets argues  
against the petition. If Saudi Arabia faces a high tariff in the 
United States, it will sell its oil elsewhere and oil from another 
country may come to the United States, these experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Further, some U.S. refineries are geared to handling certain  
products coming from Mexico and Venezuela and a shift in sources 
could require additional costs, raising prices, the experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	While the oilmen's petition is viewed as a long shot, trade  
experts say the anti-dumping provision is heavily stacked in favor 
of domestic companies and a favorable ruling is possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Clinton administration would prefer this case go away. The  
question is whether legally they can let it go away,'' says Litan, 
the Brookings economist. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990808.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 10:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aging Titans Owner Wants Super Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee Titans owner Bud Adams is in a  
league of his own. And he wants out of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams' franchise is the only one of the original eight AFL teams  
that has never made it to a Super Bowl. The 76-year-old Texas 
oilman who has owned the team since its inception in 1959 knows 
that all too well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every owner wants to get into the Super Bowl, and my desire's  
still strong. I'm getting old. I've got to get in there pretty 
soon,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	His team, known as the Oilers until February, has been close  
twice, losing the 1978 and 1979 AFC championship games to eventual 
champion Pittsburgh. They have never gotten past the divisional 
playoffs since. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, after three straight 8-8 seasons, Adams has made it clear  
he expects improvement. The team has a new stadium and new 
state-of-the-art practice facility, and all its key players back. 
That should add up to a playoff berth, Adams believes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking for this team with the new stadium and the new  
practice facility to really come out and show something this 
year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, Adams was among the NFL's most hands-on owners. Some  
saw him as a meddler. Last month, saying he had to spend more time 
on his oil business, Adams relinquished the title of team president 
to Jeff Diamond, the 1998 NFL Executive of the Year when he was a 
vice president with the Minnesota Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still would like to be working with the Titans full-time,  
but it's not in the books,'' Adams said at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams played college football at Menlo and Kansas, where he got  
an engineering degree, then moved to Houston in 1946 and made his 
fortune drilling for oil. Later, he expanded into farming, 
ranching, car dealerships and real estate and Indian artifacts. 
</P>
<P>
	He sponsored amateur teams in softball and basketball, and got  
into professional football in 1959 when he helped Lamar Hunt found 
the American Football League. The Oilers, behind Billy Cannon and 
George Blanda, won the AFL's first two championships and Adams was 
the toast of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he is reviled in his hometown for uprooting the Oilers and  
moving them to Tennessee in 1997. In Nashville, critics consider 
him a carpetbagger who played on the city's strong desire for an 
NFL team to get taxpayers to cough up $292 million for a new 
stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams knows he still has work to do in Nashville, where fans  
were disappointed when he had his team play its first season in 
Memphis and upset by the high ticket prices charged when the team 
played its second season at Vanderbilt Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``In time the fans ... will understand that NFL football is  
exciting and that this new stadium will be the place to be. It'll 
really be a fun affair. But we've just got to go through it and let 
them see that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams said he never wanted to leave Houston but had no choice  
because the city refused to build a new stadium that would help 
keep the team competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``Really the Astrodome was a baseball stadium not really built  
with football lines in mind,'' Adams said. ``It just wasn't a good 
stadium to be in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's not the case with 67,700-seat Adelphia Coliseum on the  
banks of the Cumberland River in downtown Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium features 144 luxury suites and club seating, with  
revenue from those going to Adams. The city's contract with Adams 
also gives him parking, concessions and naming rights that will 
bring the team $30 million over the next 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Astrodome, Adams had to pay rent and watch most of the  
stadium's revenue go to the Astros' ownership. As the dome aged, 
the Oilers began losing and attendance started dropping. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Adams wishes he could have stayed in Houston, where the  
Astros now are waiting for a new stadium to be completed. City 
officials also are talking of a new arena for the Rockets and 
businessman Bob McNair hopes to land an NFL expansion franchise 
with plans for a new football stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're talking about spending a billion dollars on three  
stadiums,'' said Adams, who had wanted a facility similar to San 
Antonio's Alamodome that he could share with the Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	If McNair does land a franchise, he won't be able to revive the  
Oilers name. NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue agreed last year to 
retire that nickname. 
</P>
<P>
	By changing his team's nickname to the Titans and getting a new  
logo and uniform design, Adams finally has Tennessee fans warming 
up to his teams after two years of lackluster commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale of personal seat licenses for the new stadium gives the  
team a season ticket base of more than 49,000, which ensures its 
best home attendance since 1993. And team merchandise is selling 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Adams knows his team must win to keep its new fans happy.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think having a winning season is going to satisfy the  
fans. They're going to want to get in the playoffs and hopefully go 
to the Super Bowl,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
