<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 13:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goh: Singapore Economy To Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said  
Sunday that the country's economy should grow by a stunning 4 to 5 
percent this year, up from the government's earlier prediction that 
the economy will show growth of up to 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Singapore economy is recovering from the regional  
financial crisis,'' Goh said a national address. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the economy grew by a ``very strong'' 6.7 percent in the  
second quarter of this year, bringing growth for the first half of 
1999 to 3.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Singapore economy should continue to recover in the second  
half of the year,'' Goh said, adding that the Ministry of Trade and 
Industry has revised its GDP growth forecast for 1999 to between 4 
and 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	GDP is the measure of all goods and services produced within a  
country. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a pretty sensible, conservative prediction, taking into  
account the performance in the second quarter,'' said Friedrich Wu, 
vice-president of economic research at Development Bank of 
Singapore. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without uncertainties in Asia, the Singapore economy could  
recover to a higher degree,'' Wu told The Associated Press Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	This rich city-state of 3.2 million was hit by the regional  
economic crisis in late 1997 and grew by only 0.3 percent in 1998. 
But the economy showed signs of recovery by expanding by 0.8 
percent in the first quarter this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Goh warned that the recovery is far from complete.  
</P>
<P>
	The unemployment rate, currently at 3.9 percent, is still higher  
than before the crisis, and financial services still have not 
completely recovered. He also cited ``external uncertainties'' that 
may stall Singapore's recovery, such as Japan's continuing economic 
crisis and developments in Indonesia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
