<HEADLINE> Menifee Wins Haskell at Monmouth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OCEANPORT, N.J. (AP) -- Trainer Elliott Walden made all the right  
decisions and Menifee did the rest, roaring down the stretch to win 
the $1 million Haskell Invitation Sunday by a half-length at 
Monmouth Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Walden, who is on a roll with victories in the Whitney, Haskell  
and Jim Dandy in the last week, scratched Ecton Park from the 
Haskell Friday and in favor of the Jim Dandy at Saratoga Sunday, 
which he won easily. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Menifee who went off as the 3-2 favorite, stalked  
Forestry and Cat Thief from the halfway mark. Then Menifee, ridden 
by Pat Day, rushed past his two rivals to win in 1:48.6. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great performance,'' said Day. ``This was reminiscent  
of his races in the Derby and the Preakness (both seconds) after 
that disappointment in the Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been coming around and was even better today,'' added  
Day, who had a choice of riding either Menifee or second place 
finisher Cat Thief. 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, Cat Thief and Menifee have faced each other five  
times now and Menifee has won them all. The win was Menifee's third 
of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He obviously likes this track,'' said Walden referring to the  
sire where Menifee broke his maiden in his first race last summer. 
``It was a good omen coming back to the me track for the first 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee's win was worth $600,000 and increased his lifetime  
earnings to $1,485,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee paid $5.00, 2.80 and 2.10. Cat Thief paid 3.20 and 2.20  
and Forestry was 2.10 to show. 
  	   	
</P>
