<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Price Increase Slows Somewhat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMARILLO, Calif. (AP) -- The steady increase in gasoline prices  
slowed to about 2 cents over the past two weeks and may drop 
further because of flattening crude oil prices, an industry analyst 
said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The national weighted average on Friday, including all grades  
and taxes, was $1.2849, up 1.78 cents from the previous survey 
conducted July 23, said Trilby Lundberg, publisher of the Lundberg 
Survey of 10,000 gas stations nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline prices had jumped 5 cents during the previous survey,  
so this increase marks a slowing, Ms. Lundberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Immediate increases in crude oil prices are not likely,'' she  
said. ``So gasoline price increases should weaken further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prices had reached their highest point in more than 18 months in  
July partly because of production cuts by the Organization of the 
Petroleum Exporting Countries, as well as recovering Asian and 
Latin American economies. 
</P>
<P>
	Since crude oil prices are not rising as much as they were  
during last month's high point, hikes in gas prices should slow as 
well, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The caveat is the West Coast is still short of gas due to  
refinery problems,'' she said. In the past two weeks, prices in the 
West jumped about 4 1/2 cents per gallon, while prices dropped in the 
Midwest, Ms. Lundberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices rose nearly 7 cents in Reno, Nev., but fell about 3 cents  
in Indianapolis, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	At self-serve pumps, the average for regular unleaded was  
$1.2308, mid-grade was $1.3297 and premium was $1.4153. 
</P>
<P>
	For full-service, regular was $1.5596, mid-grade averaged  
$1.6497 and premium $1.7212. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
