<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge, Lawyer Sue Tobacco Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A Mississippi judge and a lawyer are alleging that  
the nation's third largest tobacco company illegally obtained 
private phone records in an effort to intimidate and discredit them 
during a second-hand smoke trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Billy Joe Landrum and plaintiffs attorney Cynthia Langston  
claim in separate lawsuits that lawyers for Brown &AMP; Williamson 
Tobacco Corp. invaded their privacy in 1997 as part of a conspiracy 
to have the judge removed from the case, The Dallas Morning News 
reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers for the tobacco company spread rumors that  
Landrum and Langston were involved in a romantic relationship, said 
Jeff Reynolds, a lawyer representing the pair. 
</P>
<P>
	``They wanted so badly to prove that Judge Landrum and Cindy  
were having an affair because that would obviously mean they were 
meeting privately without the defense being present, and that's 
improper,'' Reynolds said. ``The only problem for them was, it 
wasn't true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuits, filed in October 1998, also allege tobacco company  
lawyers conspired with phone company employee Michael Miller, 
Langston's ex-husband, to access the phone records. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers representing Brown &AMP; Williamson and its law firm deny  
they obtained the phone records. They describe the allegations as 
baseless and frivolous and asked a judge to dismiss the cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell South Communications and Miller, who are also defendants,  
have denied involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations, if true, could violate Mississippi fraud and  
theft statutes as well as federal laws prohibiting the improper 
taking of privately stored electronic communications and data for 
commercial gain, according to lawyers in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Langston represented Ava Dean Butler in her lawsuit in which she  
alleged her husband's 1994 death stemmed from second-hand smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	During the trial, tobacco lawyers complained that Landrum  
constantly ruled against them. He became the first judge in the 
country to rule that previously secret internal industry documents 
should be made public. 
</P>
<P>
	In June 1997, an anonymous note on the letterhead of an industry  
law firm claimed ``unethical behavior'' on the part of members of 
the defense team. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter alleged meetings between Miller and George Hewes, a  
Jackson, Miss., lawyer who was lead counsel for Brown &AMP; Williamson 
in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewes said in sworn depositions that he met or called Miller  
four times during the case but never asked for nor received any 
phone records. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Miller suggested there was improper contact between  
Langston and Landrum, who have sworn under oath they had no 
romantic relationship nor any improper private meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge, frustrated with the rumors, resigned from the Butler  
case, which the tobacco companies later won at trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The verdict is being appealed.  
</P>
<P>
	Bell South fired Miller and conducted an internal investigation.  
The company has yet to disclose its findings. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
