<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Found Alive in Bering Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Six Russians whose skiffs were lost for  
four days as they made their way home across the Bering Sea have 
been found and rescued. 
</P>
<P>
	The six boaters in three skiffs were found in good condition.  
They were part of a group of 37 people, mainly Siberian Eskimos, 
who had set out Tuesday in 14 skiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The boaters had become separated from the larger group while  
making the 65-mile Bering Strait crossing from St. Lawrence Island 
off Alaska's west coast to Provideniya on Russia's Chukotka 
Peninsula 
</P>
<P>
	A Coast Guard plane spotted four people in two skiffs on  
Saturday, about 30 miles east of Provideniya, Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. 
Brian Flory said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	A short time later, two others in a third skiff were spotted by  
a Russian freighter. All six were hungry and thirsty, but did not 
appear to be seriously injured, Flory said. 
</P>
<P>
	They were making the six-hour crossing loaded with supplies and  
gifts from relatives and friends in Gambell. Many residents of 
Russia's Chukotka Peninsula share the same Siberian Yupik Eskimo 
ancestry and language with residents of St. Lawrence Island. 
</P>
<P>
	The flotilla ran into rough seas during the crossing. Two people  
-- a father and son -- drowned when their skiff sank. The Coast Guard 
said the boaters had departed without survival gear or flotation 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard had launched an intensive airborne search for  
the missing skiffs late Tuesday night. The search was called off 
Friday, but resumed Saturday after the Coast Guard received 
permission from Russian authorities to search on the Russian side 
of the maritime boundary. 
</P>
<P>
	A C-130 transport plane was able to drop a radio, food, gasoline  
and supplies to two of the boats Saturday. The survivors were taken 
aboard a Russian freighter bound for Provideniya and later were 
joined by the other missing boaters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
