<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US To Make Example of bin Laden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Orrin Hatch says the United States knows  
where Osama bin Laden is, generally knows what the alleged 
terrorist leader is doing and is aware that top Arabs are funneling 
money to him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He does have the finances, he does have some support around  
the world that literally could cause him to penetrate our country 
as well as others,'' Hatch, a member of the Senate Intelligence 
Committee and GOP presidential aspirant, said Sunday on CBS' ``Face 
the Nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the Utah Republican predicted the United States eventually  
will get to the expatriate Saudi and make an example of him. He 
refused to say whether that might include assassination. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't comment on that,'' Hatch said, but he added: ``The  
CIA, FBI and others are right on top of it. We know where he is, we 
basically know what his activities are, and we've just got to stay 
ever alert. ... This menace has got to end someday, and I think 
we'll find some way of doing that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By presidential directive, U.S. intelligence agencies are  
forbidden from using assassination as a tactic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately, we're going to get (bin Laden),'' Hatch said.  
``And ultimately, we're going to make an example of a person who 
literally is causing death all over the world, or at least trying 
to cause death all over the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch's comments came a year after 224 people, including 12  
Americans, were killed in bomb attacks on two U.S. embassies in 
Africa. U.S. officials say the almost simultaneous bombings on Aug. 
7, 1998, were orchestrated by bin Laden. 
</P>
<P>
	Bin Laden ``is one of the wealthiest terrorists and one of the  
most respected by those who love terrorism,'' Hatch said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do have some problems ... but we've kept him in check  
geographically. We're putting a lot of pressure on him all over the 
world.'' Bin Laden is thought to be hiding in Afghanistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch said Americans have a mistaken idea that bin Laden's  
organization, known as Al Khada, Arabic for ``the base,'' is a 
well-oiled terrorism machine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Al Khada is kind of loosely organized, but it's got a lot of  
fanatical people in it who basically think they're doing Allah's 
will, some of them,'' Hatch said. ``Some of them are just plain 
downright hardhearted criminals.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
